[[File:LindealleKildeparkenForaar2009.JPG|thumbnail|Kildeparken]]
'''Kildeparken''' (locally, "Kilden") is a large public park in [[Aalborg]], [[Denmark]]. It is bounded by the streets Europahallen, [[Vesterbro, Copenhagen|Vesterbro]], Old Kærvej, and the railway. It is possible to reach it from [[John F. Kennedys Plads]] through a tunnel. The park features a small lake with a fountain, sculptures, an open-air stage, and ”the Singing Trees” which were planted by notable artists.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kildeparken|url=http://www.visitaalborg.com/ln-int/denmark/kildeparken-gdk596185|publisher=Visit Aalborg|accessdate=1 September 2013}}</ref> Said to be the oldest park of Aalborg,   the park boasts traditional statues like the Three Graces by [[Bertel Thorvaldsen]] (1770–1844) and the Bacchus Child by [[Anne Marie Carl-Nielsen]].<ref name=michelin>{{cite web|title=Kildeparken|url=http://travel.michelin.com/web/destination/Scandinavia-Denmark-Alborg/tourist_site-Kildeparken-Vesterbro|publisher=Travel Michelin.Com|accessdate=2 September 2013}}</ref>   The park hosts concerts and is the center of [[Aalborg Carnival]], an annual event.<ref name=youtube>{{cite web|title=Kildeparken - Aalborg Karneval 2012 - Denmark|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2TCMonksOKE|publisher=YouTube|accessdate=2 September 2013}}</ref><ref name=denmark>{{cite web|title=Kildeparken|url=http://www.visitdenmark.es/ga/denmark/kildeparken-gdk596185|publisher=Visit Denmark.Es|accessdate=2 September 2013}}</ref>

