{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2014}} '''Klaus Jankuhn''' (born 12 January 1965) is a German record producer and musician, considered a pioneer in the early German [[techno]] scene. He mostly worked for the artists of the rave label [[Low Spirit]], producing artists such as [[WestBam]], [[Marusha]] or [[Fabian Lenz|DJ Dick]]. Together with WestBam he also founded the project [[Members of Mayday]].
== Life == Klaus Jankuhn grew up in [[Münster]], where he befriended with WestBam. Both started producing tracks for the early techno and rave scene. Around 1986 he moved to [[Berlin]].<ref>[http://www.berliner-zeitung.de/archiv/der-dj-klaus-jankuhn-produziert-mit-seinem-label-low-spirit-seit-jahren-die-hits-der-techno-szene-tschumm--tschu--tschakataka--tschumm--tschu,10810590,9164386.html Tschumm, tschu, tschakataka, tschumm, tschu], berliner-zeitung.de, retrieved 19 February 2014</ref>
One of their first tracks ''17 – This is not a [[Boris Becker]] Song'' was released in 1985 under the moniker ''Cowboy Temple''. Soon after Jankuhn, WestBam, Fabian Lenz and [[William Röttger]] founded the label Low Spirit.
Jankuhn and WestBam also produced the anthems for the annual [[Mayday (music festival)|Mayday festivals]] (as ''[[Members of Mayday]]'') and [[Love Parade]]s (as ''[[The Love Committee]]'').
== Awards == * 1995: [[Echo (music award)|Echo Pop]] as "Best producer national“ * 2003: [[Dance Music Award]] as "Best producer" (shared with WestBam)<ref>[http://board.rellek.org/threads/german-dance-award-2003.16493/ German Dance Award 2003] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203012358/http://board.rellek.org/threads/german-dance-award-2003.16493/ |date=3 December 2013 }}, rellek.org, retrieved 19 February 2014</ref>
