{{Coord|35|54|58|N|14|29|10.4|E|display=title}} {{Infobox bridge |bridge_name= Manwel Dimech Bridge |image=[[File:Manwel Dimech Bridge.jpg|300px]] |caption=East view |official_name= |carries=Four lanes |crosses=Wied Għomor |locale=[[San Ġiljan]], [[Malta]] |maint= |id= |design= |mainspan= |length= {{convert|130|m|ft|1|abbr=on}} |width= {{convert|32|m|ft|1|abbr=on}} |height= |clearance= |below= {{convert|40|m|ft|1|abbr=on}} |traffic= |open= {{Start date and age|1971|09|18|df=yes}} |life= [[box girder bridge|Modern bridge]] |closed= |map_cue= |map_image= |map_text= |map_width= |coordinates= {{Coord|35|54|58|N|14|29|10.4|E}} |lat= |long= }}
'''Manwel Dimech Bridge''' is a beam bridge at [[San Ġiljan]], [[Malta]]. It is named after [[Manuel Dimech]], and was officially inaugurated on 18 September 1971 by the Minister of Public Works, Lorry Sant. The bridge is approximately 130m long and 32m wide, and spans over Wied Għomor. It is part of [[Michael Anthony Vassalli|Mikiel Anton Vassalli]] Road (popularly known as Regional Road) just beyond the tunnels on the way to [[Paceville]] and [[St. Andrew's, Malta|St. Andrew’s]]. A commemorative plaque close to the bridge reports that the construction of the bridge, the road and the tunnels were aided by the Chinese government. The tunnels are named after [[Sun Yat-sen]], and the bridge on the other side of the tunnels is named after Ġużè Ellul Mercer. The bridge was thoroughly restored and reinforced in 2008.
==External links== * http://www.independent.com.mt/articles/2008-05-04/news/a-link-to-the-north-manwel-dimech-bridge-207160/ * http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20080412/local/manwel-dimech-bridge-could-reopen-next-week.203770
