{{Culture of Burundi}} Media in [[Burundi]] is controlled by the government.
==Telephone== {{main|Communications in Burundi}} In 2003 in Burundi, there were an estimated three mainline telephones for every 1,000 people; about 4,700 people were on a waiting list for telephone service installation. The same year, there were approximately nine mobile phones in use for every 1,000 people.
==Radio== :''See also: [[List of radio stations in Africa]]: Burundi and {{illm|List of radio stations in Burundi|fr|Liste des stations de radio au Burundi}}'' In 2001, there were four FM radio stations, two of which were owned by the government, including the [[Voice of the Revolution]], broadcasting in Rundi, [[Swahili language|Swahili]], [[French language|French]], and [[English language|English]]. There were eight privately owned radio stations in 2004, including [[Radio Isanganiro]], [[Bonesha FM]], and [[African Public Radio]] (RPA); all of these are broadcast in French, Rundi, and Swahili. Some stations receive funding from international donors. Transmissions can be received from [[British Broadcasting]] and [[Radio France Internationale]].
==Television== '''Television in Burundi''' was [[Timeline of the introduction of television in countries|introduced in 1984]], and began colour transmission in 1985. As of 2004 there was still only one television service, the [[Télévision Nationale du Burundi]]. This was owned by the government. In 2003, there were an estimated 220 radios and 35 television sets for every 1,000 people.
=== Main channels === {| class="wikitable" |- ! Name !! Owner !! Type !! Launched |- | [[Burundi National Radio and Television|RTNB]] || Government of Burundi || State-owned || 1984 |- | Télé Renaissance || Bernard Henri Levy<ref>http://www.rfi.fr/actufr/articles/105/article_71896.asp</ref> ||rowspan="3"| Private-owned ||rowspan="3"| 2008 |- | Héritage TV ||rowspan="2"| ? |- | TV Salama |}
==Internet== {{main|Communications in Burundi}} Burundi has launched a $25 million investment project in a fibre-optic cable network to widen access to broadband Internet and cut costs.<ref>https://www.reuters.com/article/burundi-internet-idUSL5N0KV2QD20140121</ref>
The main Internet publications in Burundi are
[[ikiriho.org|Ikiriho]] [[iwacu-burundi.org|Groupe Iwacu]] [https://regionweek.com RegionWeek] [[Igihe.bi|Igihe]] [[burundisport.com|burundisports]]
==Print==
The government issues a French-language daily, [[Le Renouveau du Burundi]], with a circulation of 20,000 in 2002, and several periodicals, including a weekly newspaper, [[Ubumwe]], published in [[Kirundi]], with a 1999 circulation of 20,000, and Burundi Chrétien. There were five private weekly papers as of 2004 and eight private Internet and fax news sheets. * ''[[Arc-en-Ciel]]'' * ''[[Burundi Chrétien]]'' * ''[[Burundi Tribune]]'' * ''[[Renouveau du Burundi|Le Renouwveau du Burundi]]'' * ''[[Ubumwe]]''
==Freedom of speech== Though there are no official restrictions upon expression or the press, the regime owns the only daily newspaper and two of the major radio stations, and information is said{{by whom|date=May 2015}} to be slanted toward pro-government opinions.
